goals.question: What is the distribution of daily high prices?
goals.rationale: This will give an idea of the range of high prices and how frequently they occur.

goals.question: What is the distribution of daily low prices?
goals.rationale: This will give an idea of the range of low prices and how frequently they occur.

code:

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['open'].plot(kind='hist', bins=50, color='blue', edgecolor='black')
    plt.axvline(data['open'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Mean: {data['open'].mean():0.2f}")
    plt.axvline(data['open'].median(), color='green', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label=f"Median: {data['open'].median():0.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('Opening Prices')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of daily opening prices?')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    plt.plot(data['date'], data['adjclose'])
    plt.title('What is the trend of the S&P 500 index over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Adjusted Close')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```

```
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.scatter(data['volume'], data['close'], alpha=0.5, color='blue')
    ax.set_xlabel('Volume')
    ax.set_ylabel('Closing Price')
    ax.set_title('What is the relationship between daily volume and closing prices?')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
```
